issue_obverse_legend_tesim: Ten Shillings. THis Indented Bill of Ten Shillings, due from the Colony of New-York to the Possessor thereof, shall be in equal value to Money, and shall be accordingly accepted by the Treasurer of this Colony, for the time being, in all publick payments, and for any Fund at any time in the Treasury. Dated, New-York 31st of May, 1709. by order of the Lieut. Governour, Council, and General Assembly of the said Colony.

Two Shillings and Six-pence. THIS BILL shall pass current for TWO SHILLINGS and SIX-PENCE, according to an Act of General Assembly of the STATE of GEORGIA, passed the Fourteenth Day of August, in the Year of our LORD One Thousand Seven Hundred and Eighty-Six. Dated the 16th Day of October, A. D. 1786.

issue_obverse_figure_description_tesim: Denomination at left and right.
issue_obverse_legend_tesim: GEORGIA. 1776. THESE are to certify, That the Sum of TWO SHILLINGS AND SIX-PENCE, is due from this Province to the Bearer hereof, the same being Part of TWELVE THOUSAND FIVE HUNDRED AND SEVENTY TWO POUNDS NINETEEN SHILLINGS STERLING, voted by PROVINCIAL CONGRESS, for taking up and sinking that Sum already issued.
